Executive Summary

This week marks significant progress across all three pillars of OSAC: VMaa=
S,
CaaS, and BMaaS. We successfully completed four demos, covering multi-tenan=
cy
foundations, the DNS API, the initial CaaS integration with BMaaS, and CI
foundations.

Roadmap: details
<https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/11YIDvxTK940j4XgyainQO5yzA9a3ppVwy5=
4oypo4eE0/edit?gid=3D552881355#gid=3D552881355>

------------------------------

This Week's Demos (May 4, 2026)VMaaS

VMaaS End-to-End Tests (Recording
<https://drive.google.com/file/d/15mjAtnJVCmt-412i2VAUbVB1PMjmsekw/view>
47:20 - 1:00:32)

   -

   Demonstrated a comprehensive test suite covering the full VM lifecycle.
   -

   Currently runs against the OSAC installer repository.
   -

   Provides a foundation for continuous integration, quality assurance, and
   regression detection.
   -

   Dedicated skills were created to support writing new E2E tests and
   debugging test failures effectively.
   -

   Follow-up Actions
   -

      Integrate presubmit jobs across all OSAC repositories.
      -

      Run all VMaaS tests in a single shared cluster/job to reduce resource
      consumption.
      -

      Investigate options to reduce cluster creation time, such as golden
      images or cluster claims.
      -

      Introducing CaaS tests.

CaaS

CaaS Integrated with Basic BMaaS (Recording
<https://drive.google.com/file/d/15mjAtnJVCmt-412i2VAUbVB1PMjmsekw/view>
3:30 - 27:05)

   -

   Demonstrated an initial CaaS workflow backed by Bare Metal as a Service.
   -

   Showed how the OSAC CLI triggers cluster creation, including bare metal
   pool and network setup.
   -

   Demonstrated how matching hosts are selected, fulfilled, and mapped to
   cluster agents.
   -

   Showed host power management through the OpenStack operator, with
   support for additional backend operators planned.
   -

   Covered cleanup and error handling for host leases.
   -

   Follow-up Actions
   -

      Add support for bare metal pool profiles - reusable definitions that
      describe which setup or cleanup actions should run when bare metal
      resources are created or released.
      -

      Move network setup and host attachment logic into profiles, instead
      of keeping it only in the CaaS workflow.
      -

      Evaluate improvements to agent selection and assignment.

Cross-Cutting Capabilities

DNS API (Recording
<https://drive.google.com/file/d/15mjAtnJVCmt-412i2VAUbVB1PMjmsekw/view>
27:15 - 34:35)

   -

   Demonstrated a generic DNS API, initially focused on CaaS.
   -

   Showed creation of required cluster DNS records, including external API,
   internal API, and ingress records.
   -

   Replaced hard-coded Route 53 logic with an extensible dispatcher and
   backend driver model.
   -

   Implemented Route 53 as the first backend.
   -

   Follow-up Actions
   -

      Add support for additional DNS backends.
      -

      Expand DNS API usage across VMaaS workflows.

Organization Multi-Tenancy (Recording
<https://drive.google.com/file/d/15mjAtnJVCmt-412i2VAUbVB1PMjmsekw/view>
34:40 - 47:10)

   -

   Demonstrated the initial multi-tenancy flow using Keycloak for
   authentication and authorization.


   -

   Showed how an OSAC organization can be created and managed through the
   OSAC CLI.
   -

   Explained that each organization currently maps to a Keycloak realm.
   -

   Showed creation of a break-glass account for emergency access if the
   identity provider connection fails.
   -

   Follow-up Actions
   -

      Move from Keycloak realms to Keycloak organizations.
      -

      Define roles for tenant admins, tenant users, and provider admins.
      -

      Add APIs for role management and RBAC.
      -

      Allow break-glass password changes through OSAC.
      -

      Add support for multiple projects under the same organization/tenant.

------------------------------

Upcoming Demos:

   -

   UI for VMaaS - initial UI for VMaaS.
   -

   Optional dedicated VM clusters - running VMs on a separate cluster
   instead of the main management cluster.
   -

   VM Public IP - Virtual machines with public IP addresses via CUDN +
   MetalLB
   -

   VM Status Reporting - Improved status reports include the specific steps
   executed within Ansible roles.
   -

   Cluster API - Demo of an extended cluster configuration API that
   introduces defined attributes, moving beyond the current minimal model t=
hat
   only supports templates and template parameters.
   -

   VAST Storage - Initial implementation to enable CaaS with VAST storage,
   without yet integrating with OSAC=E2=80=99s generic storage APIs.
   -

   Storage Tenant Onboarding - Provision per tenant storage class on tenant
   creation
   -

   CaaS auto provisioning - Periodic inventory sync and agent creation.
   -

   Catalog Items - adds a user-facing layer above Ansible templates,
   allowing providers to expose multiple curated provisioning options that =
can
   reuse the same underlying Ansible role.


=F0=9F=91=89 Weekly Demo Schedule: View Schedule
<https://docs.google.com/document/d/1V7uxuxJNyK2pkoaTQ3TJngnNp2ktvZzTAJMUES=
v0U4M/edit?tab=3Dt.3nl8xrjatv13>

------------------------------

Blockers and Risks

   -

   Inventory system integration - Today, inventory is file-based. We need
   to add support for additional inventory systems, potentially including B=
CM.
   -

   DPU/HBN hardware availability -  Integrating CaaS with DPU/HBN is a high
   priority, but limited access to DPU hardware may slow development and
   validation.


Thanks,
Alona.

